hy]]''. New York: Grosset & Dunlap, 1973. * ''Portrait of [[Picasso]] as a Young Man: An Interpretive Biography''. Atlantic Monthly Press, 1995. * ''[[Oswald's Tale|Oswald's Tale: An American Mystery]]''. New York: Random House, 1996. {{Refend}} ==Decorations and awards== * 1969: [[Pulitzer Prize]], [[George Polk Awards|George Polk Award]], and [[National Book Award]] for ''The Armies of the Night'';{{sfn|Lennon|2013|pp=393–394}}{{sfn|Dearborn|1999|pp=7, 259}}{{sfn|Lennon|Lennon|2018|p=358}} Honorary Doctor of Letters from [[Rutgers University]]{{sfn|Lennon|Lennon|2018|p=358}} * 1970: Harvard University's [[Signet society|Signet Society]] Medal for Achievement in the Arts{{sfn|Lennon|Lennon|2018|p=359}} * 1973: [[Edward MacDowell Medal]]{{sfn|Lennon|Lennon|2018|p=361}}{{cite web |url=https://www.macdowellcolony.org/medal-day-history |title=Medal Day History |author= |website=MacDowell Colony |access-date=2018-11-12 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180730080504/https://www.macdowellcolony.org/medal-day-history |archive-date=2018-07-30 |url-status=live }} * 1975: ''[[Playboy]]'''s Best Nonfiction Award for ''The Fight''{{sfn|Lennon|Lennon|2018|p=362}} * 1976: Gold Medal for Literature by the [[National Arts Club]];{{sfn|Lennon|Lennon|2018|p=139}} ''Playboy'''s Best Major Work in Fiction Award{{sfn|Lennon|Lennon|2018|pp=361–362}} * 1979: Best Major Work in Fiction Award from ''Playboy'' for ''The Executioner's Song''{{sfn|Lennon|Lennon|2018|p=364}} * 1980: Pulitzer Prize for ''Executioner's Song''{{sfn|Dearborn|1999|p=351}} * 1984: Honorary Doctor of Letters from [[Mercy College (New York)|Mercy College]] in White Plains, NY;{{sfn|Lennon|Lennon|2018|p=366}} Inducted into the [[American Academy of Arts and Letters]]{{sfn|Lennon|Lennon|2018|pp=366–367}} * 1985: Lord and Taylor's Rose Award{{sfn|Lennon|Lennon|2018|p=367}} * 1987: [[Independent Spirit Award for Best Film|Independent Spirit Award for best film]] and [[Golden Raspberry Award for Worst Director]] (both for ''Tough Guys Don't Dance''){{sfn|Lennon|Lennon|2018|p=368}} * 1989: [[PEN Oakland awards#Josephine Miles Award|PEN Oakland / Josephine Miles Award]];{{cite web |url=https://www.penoakland.com/awards-winners/ |title=PEN Oakland Awards & Winners |author= |website=PEN Oakland |access-date=2018-11-12 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190514072907/https://www.penoakland.com/awards-winners |archive-date=2019-05-14 |url-status=dead }} [[Emerson-Thoreau Medal]]{{sfn|Lennon|Lennon|2018|p=369}} * 1991: New York State Edith Wharton Citation of Merit{{sfn|Lennon|Lennon|2018|p=361}} * 1994: Harvard University's Signet Society Medal for Achievement in the Arts{{sfn|Lennon|Lennon|2018|p=370}} * 1995: Honorary Doctor of Letters from [[Wilkes University]], in Wilkes-Barre, PA{{sfn|Lennon|Lennon|2018|pp=370–371}} * 2000: F. Scott Fitzgerald Award for Achievement in American Literature{{cite web |url=https://fscottfestival.org/festival/ |title=F. Scott Fitzgerald Literary Conference |author= |website=F. Scott Fitzgerald Literary Festival |access-date=2018-11-12 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181113075430/https://fscottfestival.org/festival/ |archive-date=2018-11-13 |url-status=live }} * 2002: Lifetime Achievement Award from the James Jones Literary Society, June 22;{{sfn|Lennon|Lennon|2018|loc=[https://projectmailer.net/pm/2002 2002]}} [[Austrian Cross of Honour for Science and Art, 1st class]]{{cite web | url = http://www.parlament.gv.at/PAKT/VHG/XXIV/AB/AB_10542/imfname_251156.pdf | title = Reply to a parliamentary question | language = de | page = 1517 | access-date = 15 January 2013 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20121022192702/http://www.parlament.gv.at/PAKT/VHG/XXIV/AB/AB_10542/imfname_251156.pdf | archive-date = 22 October 2012 | url-status = live }} * 2004: Golden Plate Award of the [[Academy of Achievement|American Academy of Achievement]]{{cite web|title= Golden Plate Awardees of the American Academy of Achievement |website=www.achievement.org|publisher=[[American Academy of Achievement]]|url= https://achievement.org/our-history/golden-plate-awards/#the-arts}} * 2005: National Book Award for Distinguished Contribution to American Letters{{sfn|Lennon|2013|p=742}} ==See also== * [[List of peace activists]] == References == === Notes === {{notelist}} {{reflist|group=lower-alpha}} === Citations === {{Reflist|20em}} === Selected bibliography === Contains important books and articles about Mailer and his works, many of which are cited in this article. See [[#Works|Works]] above for a list of Mailer's first editions and Mailer's individual works for reviews. ==== Bibliographies ==== {{Refbegin|indent=yes}} * {{cite book |last=Adams |first=Laura |date=1974 |title=Norman Mailer: A Comprehensive Bibliography |url=https://archive.org/details/normanmailercomp0000adam|url-access=registration |location=Metuchen, NJ |publisher=Scarecrow |isbn=9780810807716 |oclc=462662793 }} * {{cite journal |last1=Lennon |first1=J. Michael |date=2008b |title=Norman Mailer's Best Sellers |url=https://mailerreview.org/norman-mailer-s-bestsellers-941dcce86c5f |journal=The Mailer Review |volume=2 |issue=1 |pages=270–71 |access-date=2017-08-26 |issn=1936-4679 }} * {{cite book |last1=Lennon |first1=J. Michael |author-mask=1 |last2=Lennon| first2=Donna Pedro |editor-last=Lucas |editor-first=Gerald R. |date=2018 |title=Norman Mailer: Works and Days |edition=Revised, Expanded |url=https://prmlr.us/nmwd |location=Atlanta, GA |publisher=The Norman Mailer Society |isbn=978-1-7326519-0-6 }} Comprehensive, annotated primary and secondary bibliography with life chronology. {{Refend}} ==== Biographical studies ==== {{Refbegin|indent=yes}} * {{cite book |last=Dearborn |first=Mary V. |date=1999 |title=Mailer: A Biography |url=https://archive.org/details/mailerbiography00mary |url-access=registration |location=Boston |publisher=Houghton Mifflin |isbn=978-0395736555 }} * {{cite book |last=Lennon |first=J. Michael |date=2013 |title=Norman Mailer